==English==

===Alternative spellings===
Various authorities support the different styles:
*[[Anno Domini]]
*[[anno domini]]

===Etymology===
*Latin ''annō Domini'', from ''[[anno|annō]]'', the [[ablative]] of ''[[annus]]'' (''[[year]]'') + ''[[Domini]]'', the [[genitive]] of '''[[Dominus]]''' (''the [[Lord]]'').

===Adverb===
'''[[anno]] [[Domini]]'''

# In the year of our Lord (often abbreviated [[A.D.]] or [[AD]]). The religion-neutral [[Common Era]] ([[CE]]) is an alternative.

====Usage notes====
*The [[w:Chicago Manual of Style|Chicago Manual of Style]] as well as most house styles require placing the [[AD]] before the date (e.g., AD 250), although in casual use it is frequently found following the date.

====Synonyms====
*(''in the year of our Lord''): [[a.d.]], [[AD]], [[A.D.]], [[CE]], [[Common Era]], [[in the year of our Lord]]

====Antonyms====
*(''in the year of our Lord''): [[b.c.]], [[BC]], [[B.C.]], [[BCE]]

====Translations====
''see [[Anno Domini]]''

===See also===
*[[w:Wikipedia talk:Manual of Style (dates and numbers)/archive9|Wikipedia discussion of style]]

